Alex Webb and Rebecca Norris Webb (@webb_norriswebb) have been photographing the New York City borough of Brooklyn for the past five years, creating a profound and vibrant portrait. Together, their photographs of Brooklyn tell a larger American story, one that touches on immigration, identity, nature, and home.
.
A limited number of signed copies of 'Brooklyn, the City Within' are available on shop.magnumphotos.com now, alongside a selection of other books published by Magnum photographers this year.

WINTER STORM 
In this eerie yellow light, it seems the snow will never end. Hard to focus when the fingers are so cold. Keep thinking about those Canada geese—hundreds of wings folding under the unbearable weight of snow. How lightly they float, now, across Prospect Lake, like some half-remembered longing. How do any of us, for that matter, find our way? One January, traveling alone across the South Dakota prairie, I remember waking—half-dreaming at three a.m.—and opening my motel room door to a blizzard of geese, blown off course by an unexpected snow. Head bowed against this icy wind, I wonder how many of us now—this moment in Brooklyn—find ourselves inhabiting two worlds at once?—Rebecca Norris Webb. Photo: Rebecca Norris Webb, Winter Storm, Prospect Park, Brooklyn, 2016; both text and photo from the joint book, Brooklyn: The City Within, with Alex Webb, @aperturefnd #poetrysunday #brooklyn #rebeccanorriswebb #thecitywithin

DECEMBER NIGHT⠀
⠀
If the waxing gibbous moon is bright enough, even the emptiness of the fields shine. And on the rise in the distance, I see the beech and sycamore forest that once was.—Rebecca Norris Webb, for Martyne. LIVING AND DYING⠀
⠀
It has taken me much of my life to learn to trust my creative process, an often slow, meandering path towards understanding life and death and the world through the process of photographing—and sometimes writing about—images that intrigue me for some reason.⠀
⠀
While working on My Dakota, one of my responses to my brother’s death was writer’s block. Only at the end of the project did my writing return—spare text pieces some four lines long. They often came to me whole when I’d awake in my motel room while traveling alone through the South Dakota landscape.⠀
⠀
Once I thought I saw him—⠀
it was late fall on the Missouri⠀
the back of a brown coat vanishing into the trees. Was it a man or a deer?⠀
⠀
“To grieve is to lament, to mourn, to let sorrow inhabit one’s very being,” writes the poet Edward Hirsch. He adds, “Implicit in poetry is the notion that we are deepened by heartbreaks, that we are not so much diminished as enlarged by grief, by our refusal to vanish—to let others vanish—without leaving a poetic record.” Poet Stanley Kunitz, a close friend of Alex’s parents, used to say that to be human was “to know yourself to be living and dying at the same time.”⠀
⠀
Looking back at My Dakota, I realize that I was photographing this difficult time in my life to try to absorb it, to crystallize it, and, ultimately, to let it go. Not only did my first grief change me, but making My Dakota changed me as well, both as a human being and as an artist. —Rebecca Norris Webb. Photo: Rebecca Norris Webb Homestead Blizzard, text and image from the Aperture book, Alex Webb and Rebecca Norris Webb on Street Photography and the Poetic Image. #workshopwednesdays #rebeccanorriswebb #onstreetphotographyandthepoeticimage @aperturefnd @martynebailey

"If one photographs a place, almost inevitably one becomes aware of the weight of past photographs. However, the images that I particularly remember of Brooklyn are largely in black and white, ranging from the work of Robert Frank, Bruce Davidson, and Garry Winogrand, to more recent images from Eugene Richards, Bruce Gilden, and Thomas Roma. As a color photographer now for some 40 years, photographing Brooklyn in color has seemed like unexplored territory.”—Alex Webb, from the Brownstoner interview by Craig Hubert. See link in profile for complete interview. Photo: Alex Webb, Dumbo, Brooklyn, 2018, from the joint book, Brooklyn: The City Within, with Rebecca Norris Webb, @aperturefnd. #alexwebb #Brooklyn #thecitywithin @craighubert @brownstoner

430 AM⠀
⠀
This hour always called to you—⠀
first to rise,⠀
sipping coffee with the silence⠀
and the darkness.⠀
Now it is ours, too,⠀
when we wake early⠀
and, like you, listen⠀
for the music⠀
inside the stillness.⠀
—Rebecca Norris Webb, for Craig, December 2019, in memoriam. Photo: Rebecca Norris Webb, from the work-in-progress Night Calls, December 2019⠀
⠀
#poetrysunday⠀
#rnw_nightcalls⠀
#rebeccanorriswebb #in_memoriam

“Though I set out to photograph all over Brooklyn, I’ve never envisioned my work as any kind of complete portrait of the borough. I’ve photographed long enough to know that serendipity plays an immense role in my photography and that sometimes I simply don’t find photographs—or they don’t find me. I accept that my photography is 99.9 percent about failure.”—Alex Webb, from the @brownstoner interview by Craig Hubert about the joint book, Brooklyn: The City Within, with Rebecca Norris Webb. See link in profile for rest of interview. LET EVENING COME ⠀
⠀
Let the light of late afternoon⠀
shine through chinks in the barn, moving ⠀
up the bales as the sun moves down.⠀
⠀
Let the cricket take up chafing ⠀
as a woman takes up her needles ⠀
and her yarn. Let evening come.⠀
⠀
Let dew collect on the hoe abandoned ⠀
in long grass. Let the stars appear⠀
and the moon disclose her silver horn.⠀
⠀
Let the fox go back to its sandy den. ⠀
Let the wind die down. Let the shed ⠀
go black inside. Let evening come.⠀
⠀
To the bottle in the ditch, to the scoop ⠀
in the oats, to air in the lung ⠀
let evening come.⠀
⠀
Let it come, as it will, and don’t ⠀
be afraid. God does not leave us ⠀
comfortless, so let evening come.⠀
—Jane Kenyon, dedicated to Craig Bailey, who at 4:30 AM yesterday became the music he loved.⠀
⠀
Photo: Rebecca Norris Webb, Let Evening Come, 2019, from the work-in-progress, Night Calls⠀

THANKS⠀
⠀
Listen⠀
with the night falling we are saying thank you⠀
we are stopping on the bridges to bow from the railings⠀
we are running out of the glass rooms⠀
with our mouths full of food to look at the sky⠀
and say thank you⠀
we are standing by the water thanking it⠀
standing by the windows looking out⠀
in our directions⠀
⠀
back from a series of hospitals back from a mugging⠀
after funerals we are saying thank you⠀
after the news of the dead⠀
whether or not we knew them we are saying thank you⠀
⠀
over telephones we are saying thank you⠀
in doorways and in the backs of cars and in elevators⠀
remembering wars and the police at the door⠀
and the beatings on stairs we are saying thank you⠀
in the banks we are saying thank you⠀
in the faces of the officials and the rich⠀
and of all who will never change⠀
we go on saying thank you thank you⠀
⠀
with the animals dying around us⠀
taking our feelings we are saying thank you⠀
with the forests falling faster than the minutes⠀
of our lives we are saying thank you⠀
with the words going out like cells of a brain⠀
with the cities growing over us⠀
we are saying thank you faster and faster⠀
with nobody listening we are saying thank you⠀
thank you we are saying and waving⠀
dark though it is⠀
—W.S. Merwin, dedicated to all of our family and friends, former students, and fellow photographers, writers, and other artists on this Thanksgiving day.⠀
⠀
Photo: Rebecca Norris Webb, We Are Standing By the Windows, near Medora, North Dakota, 2019, from the work-in-progress, The Great Open, with Alex Webb.⠀

WILD IS THE WIND⠀
⠀
⠀
There’s plenty I miss, still, that I wouldn’t want back—⠀
which I’m beginning to think might be all regret’s ever had⠀
to mean, and there’s maybe no shame, then, in having⠀
known some and, all these years, I’ve pretty much⠀
been wrong. Not that being wrong means wasting time,⠀
exactly. What hasn’t been useful?⠀
—Carl Phillips, an excerpt, from the book, Wild is the Wind @fsgbooks. Photo: Rebecca Norris Webb, Genoa, 2019, from the work-in-progress, The Shimmering.
⠀
#poetrysunday⠀
#carlphillips @pinestereo

TELL IT SLANT⠀ ⠀
At its most basic, a photographer’s vision is nothing more than his or her particular gaze. My gaze tends to be dreamy and somewhat askew, as if I were looking at the world out of the corner of my eye.⠀ ⠀
Maybe that’s because I was deathly shy as a child, stealing sidelong glances at the world, lost in daydreams. Maybe reading too much poetry is to blame. Whatever the cause, I try to follow the directive of Emily Dickinson, a favorite poet of mine: “Tell all the truth but tell it slant.” —Rebecca Norris Webb. Photo: Rebecca Norris Webb, Brienna, 2013, both text and image from the Aperture book, Alex Webb and Rebecca Norris Webb on Street Photography and the Poetic Image, now in its fifth printing. #workshopwednesdays #rebeccanorriswebb #tellitslant #emilydickinson @aperturefnd ⠀

THE LIGHT BY THE BARN⠀
⠀
The light by the barn that shines all night⠀
pales at dawn when a little breeze comes.⠀
⠀
A little breeze comes breathing the fields⠀
from their sleep and waking the slow windmill.⠀
⠀
The slow windmill sings the long day⠀
about anguish and loss to the chickens at work.⠀
⠀
The little breeze follows the slow windmill⠀
and the chickens at work till the sun goes down--⠀
⠀
Then the light by the barn again.⠀
⠀
—William Stafford. Photo: Rebecca Norris Webb, Light By the Barn, 2017, for Martyne, from the work-in-progress, Night Calls. #poetrysunday #stafford #nightcalls #rebeccanorriswebb @martynebailey

MATRIMONY⠀
⠀
One night I see Saturn ––between Ninth and Tenth Streets ––naked and luminous through the glass. You look, too: white orb, the ring of your laughter. Floating home, you pull me into your chest. I’m light, mercury vapor, almost yours, until the mortal woman returns, all curves and memory, your arm ringing my waist. A gift, this distance we’ve traveled so far.—Rebecca Norris Webb, for Alex on our 20th Wedding Anniversary. ⠀
⠀
Photo: Alex Webb, Nuevo Laredo, Mexico, 1996, which I fondly call “The Becky Picture,” and which we chose as the image for our handmade invitations to our Cape Cod wedding on this day in 1999, which we still consider the best day of our lives.—Alex Webb⠀

Photo: Alex Webb, Sancti Spiritus, Cuba, 1993, part of the group exhibition, Photography from the Permanent Collection, at Provincetown Art Association and Museum (PAAM), through January 19, 2020, Provincetown, Mass. Image is from the joint book, Violet Isle: A Duet of Photographs from Cuba, with Rebecca Norris Webb @radius.books. #alexwebb #cuba #paam @paam1914

This World is not Conclusion.
A Species stands beyond—
Invisible, as Music—
But positive, as Sound…
—Emily Dickinson, an excerpt from the poem. Photo: Rebecca Norris Webb, Cloud, from the work-in-progress, Night Calls. #poetrysunday #emilydickinson #rebeccanorriswebb
